2014 IEEE 13th International Conference on Trust, Security and Privacy in Computing and Communications
Adaptive Sharing for Online Social Networks: A Trade-oÔ¨Ä between Privacy Risk and Social BeneÔ¨Åt

Mu Yang, Yijun Yu, Arosha K. Bandara The Open University, UK

Bashar Nuseibeh The Open University, UK and Lero, Ireland

Abstract‚ÄîOnline social networks such as Facebook allow users to control which friend sees what information, but it can be a laborious process for users to specify every receiver for each piece of information they share. Therefore, users usually group their friends into social circles, and select the most appropriate social circle to share particular information with. However, social circles are not formed for setting privacy policies, and even the most appropriate social circle still cannot adapt to the changes of users‚Äô privacy requirements inÔ¨Çuenced by the changes in context. This problem drives the need for better privacy control which can adaptively Ô¨Ålter the members in a selected social circle to satisfy users‚Äô requirements while maintaining users‚Äô social needs. To enable such adaptive sharing, this paper proposes a utility-based trade-oÔ¨Ä framework that models users‚Äô concerns (i.e. potential privacy risks) and incentives of sharing (i.e. potential social beneÔ¨Åts), and quantiÔ¨Åes users‚Äô requirements as a tradeoÔ¨Ä between these two types of utilities. By balancing these two metrics, our framework suggests a subset of a selected circle that aims to maximise users‚Äô overall utility of sharing. Numerical simulation results compare the outcome of three sharing strategies in randomly changing contexts.
I. Introduction
Online social networks provide people new opportunities for interaction and socialization. As a result, users‚Äô personal information, including proÔ¨Åle data, location and activities are increasingly shared with online friends via online social networks, comprising families, friends, coworkers and even strangers. With the dramatically increased number of users and amount of information sharing, the question of whether online social networks provide users good privacy control over their personal information is particularly important.
Online social networks such as Facebook and Google+ allow users to control which friends see what information, but users who are not aware of privacy often share information without considering who should (or should not) access it. Even privacy-aware users sometimes may make wrong decisions because of a lack of skill and information about risks and consequences of sharing [2], [17]. Moreover, specifying every receiver for each piece of information they share can be a laborious precess, especially when they have several hundreds of online friends [13]. Users thus usually share information by choosing the most appropriate social circle from their predeÔ¨Åned social circles which are grouped according to diÔ¨Äerent types of relationships, e.g., family, classmate, living in the same city, etc. However, social circles are not formed for setting privacy policies, and rather are relatively static groupings of diÔ¨Äerent types of friends [15]. For privacy management, users require dynamic social circles to match each of their sharing intentions, and these social circles must be able to adapt to the changes of users‚Äô privacy requirements which are

inÔ¨Çuenced by contextual factors [5], [16], such as sensitivity of information, trustworthiness of information receivers, etc. However, these changes are not predictable when forming social circles. Therefore, better privacy control is needed, which can capture these changes at runtime and then adaptively Ô¨Ålter the members in users‚Äô selected sharing circles each time before sharing their information.
There have been several attempts to solve this adaptive sharing problem [3], [6], [4]. These studies make the assumption that users are privacy-aware and their historical sharing decisions do not cause privacy problems. They proposed schemes that automatically form new social circles to adapt to users‚Äô changing context and sharing requirements, by predicting users‚Äô decisions based on their historical ones. However, because users may make poor decisions, these schemes may adversely aÔ¨Äect users‚Äô privacy. A novel approach to determine the optimal sharing decision within the selected social circle rather than just predict decisions that are most likely to be chosen remains an open research topic. In particular, it requires an analytical framework to predict, quantify and trade-oÔ¨Ä the potential privacy risks and social beneÔ¨Åt with respect to each of the information receivers in the selected social circle. This is a challenging and fundamental problem. Indeed, if we cannot quantify and trade-oÔ¨Ä these, we will not be able to determine with whom users should share in the selected social circle, given particular information in a given context. The trade-oÔ¨Ä between the potential social gains and privacy risks of sharing requires users‚Äô own preferences over them, and hence users must be involved and the framework must be able to take into account users‚Äô preferences every time they share.
Simplifying social networking scenarios on the basis of two popular privacy threats [8], we assume four possible activities information receivers may undertake regarding the information: re-share, misuse, respond, and do nothing. We will describe the details of our threat model and these activities in ¬ßII. Given the threat model and these four activities, we select several contextual factors for the quantiÔ¨Åcation of potential sharing risks and beneÔ¨Åts. By using these factors, we illustrate how to build a utility-based trade-oÔ¨Ä framework that quantiÔ¨Åes users‚Äô privacy risks and social beneÔ¨Åt for sharing their information with each of the members in the selected sharing circle. We then study the trade-oÔ¨Äs between these two types of utility under diÔ¨Äerent settings of these factors. Finally the trade-oÔ¨Äs enable our solution for adaptive sharing to recommend that users should share information within an optimally selected social circle, adapting to changing contextual factors at runtime. The eÔ¨Äectiveness of our adaptive sharing framework is evaluated with a simulation of randomised contextual factors.

