C. Metrics for predicting social beneÔ¨Åt

In the previous section we developed an informationtheoretic model that quantiÔ¨Åes users‚Äô potential privacy risks in terms of the sharing behaviours. In this section we focus on users‚Äô social beneÔ¨Åt bi j(S) and measure how much user i is predicted to gain by sharing infoi with j. In this paper, the social gains are evaluated by considering the following two aspects.

‚Ä¢ User i gains social beneÔ¨Åt if her information is seen by information receiver j and j belongs to the selected sharing circle. We denote this beneÔ¨Åt as Œ¶(i1j)(S).
‚Ä¢ Interactions between i and j. As described in the respond activity in ¬ßII, due to the sharing, user i has opportunities to interact with j. In particular, j may comment on i‚Äôs sharing, or show her opinions (e.g., Like), or any kind of responses to it. They may then have further interactions regarding j‚Äôs responses. This type of social beneÔ¨Åt is denoted by Œ¶(i2j)(S).
In order to capture the essence of these two aspects, we Ô¨Årst deÔ¨Åne a general function of social beneÔ¨Åt as a combination of all types of beneÔ¨Åt.

DeÔ¨Ånition 6: (Social beneÔ¨Åt) For user i, the social beneÔ¨Åt bi j(S) describes the social payoÔ¨Ä to her under her strategies S in terms of information receiver j. We assume that the utility function of social beneÔ¨Åt takes the form of a linear combination of functions Œ¶(iŒ≤j), each accounting for a type Œ≤ of social beneÔ¨Åt, relevant to the speciÔ¨Åc application. That is, using a weight parameter viŒ≤ ‚â• 0 to indicate the (relative) weight that user i attributes to type Œ≤, then Œ≤ viŒ≤ = 1 and
bi j(S) = viŒ≤ ¬∑ Œ¶(iŒ≤j ).
