V. Related Work
We have identiÔ¨Åed several attempts to solve the adaptive sharing problem.
Fabeah, et al. [3] proposed the idea of developing an automated grouping technique that analyzes users‚Äô social graph and sharing behaviours, and then identiÔ¨Åes new social circles to give users usable and meaningful groupings of friends for sharing their information. This approach enables users to choose a more suitable social circle when they want to share a particular information, but it cannot eÔ¨Äectively adapt to users‚Äô changing privacy requirement and context as the circles are derived without considering these important factors.
Fang and LeFevre [6] proposed a template for the design of a social networking privacy wizard. The idea is to let users assign ‚Äúlabels‚Äù (e.g., share or not share) to a set of selected friends, then by taking these as inputs for their machine learning model, the wizard generates the same (resp. opposite) labels for the other remaining friends who are in the same (resp. diÔ¨Äerent) circle. The wizard asks users‚Äô sharing opinions for the selected friends each time users initiate a sharing, and seems to adaptively satisfy users‚Äô changing requirements of information-sharing. However, this approach works well under two assumptions: friends in the same social circle bring the user the same consequences of sharing, and users are able to understand the risks of sharing and are fully privacy-aware.
Bilogrevic et al. [4] built an adaptive information-sharing system for mobile social networks. The system uses a machine learning approach to monitor users‚Äô sharing decisions under diÔ¨Äerent contexts. Then the system predicts decisions for new sharing requests based on these previous decisions and new context as well. The system also assumes users are fully privacy-aware, but the assumption may not be true for average users in real world and by using this system, users‚Äô privacy is not better protected.
In this paper, we focus on a utility-based trade-oÔ¨Ä framework that models the consequences of sharing into utilities by taking into account users‚Äô privacy preferences, social requirements and as well as contextual factors. By evaluating diÔ¨Äerent utilities under diÔ¨Äerent sharing decisions, we obtain an optimal decision and recommend it to users to support their decisionmaking. Acquisti [2] discussed the economics literature that relates to trading-oÔ¨Ä the loss against beneÔ¨Åt of sharing personal information. Squicciarini and GriÔ¨Én [14] studied how users

decide whether to disclose, share or lie about their information in a game-theoretic approach by evaluating their utilities under these three strategies. In their model, the beneÔ¨Åt and loss of sharing are deÔ¨Åned as two generalized functions and their evaluations for real applications have not been investigated. Ioannidis, Pym and Williams [7] developed a mathematical model to Ô¨Ånd the optimal decisions for organizations when they deploy information security policies. This study models the trade-oÔ¨Äs among several properties of information security by combining the measurements of these properties into a utility function.
Another challenge explored in this paper is the measurement of privacy risks and social beneÔ¨Åt. We try to predict and measure the information leaked to unintended recipients and untrusted friends who cause the potential privacy loss. In this paper, a measuring model is proposed based on Shannon‚Äôs entropy [12] and combined with the sensitivity of the sharing information, users‚Äô privacy loss is computed. A similar work was done by Liu and Terzi [11] and they deÔ¨Åned a mathematically sound methodology for computing users‚Äô privacy scores of their privacy settings in online social networks. They took the sensitivity of the sharing information as the main factor, and the more sensitive a user shares the lower score the user gets. Unlike this work, we consider the amount of information leakage as also an important and necessary factor. Even though some information has high sensitivity, the potential privacy risk is zero if it is not leaked to any unintended recipients or untrustworthy friends.
VI. Conclusion and Future Work
Privacy management is an important problem in online social networks. Existing privacy control is neither adequate nor eÔ¨Äective in adaptively deciding the sharing circles to satisfy users‚Äô changing sharing requirements in diÔ¨Äerent contexts.
This paper has proposed a utility-based trade-oÔ¨Ä framework that models and quantiÔ¨Åes users‚Äô adaptive sharing requirements as utility of potential privacy risks and social beneÔ¨Åt. By balancing these two metrics, the proposed framework recommends users a subset of the selected sharing circle each time they initiate an information-sharing action, which can always maximise users‚Äô overall utility. Numerical simulations show that our approach of adaptive sharing outperforms ‚Äúalways sharing‚Äù and ‚Äúprobabilistic sharing‚Äù, especially when the information is highly sensitive. The simulations also show that the re-share restriction is eÔ¨Äective for protecting privacy.
We plan to extend our approach in the following directions. First, we plan to further investigate adaptive sharing problem

